AB  - The United States Supreme Court judgment rendered in Cherokee Nation v. Georgia (1831) has been considered one of the ten worst decisions for Indian law (Echo Hawk, 2010). More recently, in 2013, the United States Supreme Court ruled on the water conflict presented in Tarrant Regional Water District, Petitioner v. Rudolf John Herrmann Et Al. No. 11-889 (2013) (SCOTUS, 2013). Documents for this case brought into question whether American Indian rights were being adequately presented (Burrage, 2013; Chapman, 1985; Greetham, 2008; Sotomayor, 2013; Verrilli, Jr., 2012). Historical analysis of events and documents reveal the depths of social inequality evident in the conflict between powerful federal and state agencies and marginalized groups. A case study, utilizing Ritzer's integrative theory of social analysis, asks whether the Red River Compact, the water allocation document between the states of Oklahoma, Texas, Arkansas, and Louisiana, grants favorable benefits to one state over another. This case study helps identify whether American Indian water rights have been adequately considered.
