T1  - Racism as a Predictor of Psychological Distress in a Sample of Trinidadian College Students
AN  - 914768013; 201200192
AB  - This study is an investigation of race-related stress as a predictor of psychological distress and self-esteem among Afro-Trinidadians, Indo-Trinidadians and Trinidadians of mixed ancestry. One hundred seventy-eight Trinidadian participants from a university sample completed the Index of Race-Related Stress (IRSS)-Brief version, the Symptom Checklist-90 Revised, and the Coopersmith Self-Esteem Inventory. Analysis of variance revealed that though self-esteem did not vary among the Trinidadian racial groups, indications of psychological distress varied widely. Results from multiple regression analyses indicated that perceived institutional racism did not predict self-esteem, but it significantly predicted psychological distress. In addition, each of the three race-related stress variables (i.e., individual racism, institutional racism, and cultural racism) suggested significant differences among the three racial groups. The implications of these findings are discussed in the context of race relations in Trinidad. Adapted from the source document.
